>>41739759
It gets really damn boring if I can skim several pages because there's no new info, no conflicts advanced or refined, or anything except "tell me for the 9001th time about minor quirks"
Filler is a garnish
Character-based stories have the same minor beats that plot-based stories do, and if they don't the pacing drags
When that happens, you get the reader asking the writer what was so important that they had to see/hear this

If you've never done it, take something you wrote and cut it down to half the size
This especially goes for dialogue
Tightly written dialogue does everything you said without wandering off
If the story doesn't warrant the "just shoot the shit", then tighten up
If it does because it's character-based, then the beats confirm the character arcs are moving

tl;dr if your dialogue doesn't have beats, you've already passed slowburn and arrived in Bloatville

Anonymous Sun 19 Sep 2021 12:52:02 No.41747678 Report
Quoted By: >>41748299
>>41741804
HFY was a good idea at the outset, echoes of which we still see in material posted here and the better science fiction. The name itself reflects the bullshit narcissism that took over the whole thing, though. Originally the point was to move away from treating humanity as the boring standard in science fiction, encouraging people to consider how weird we are even compared to other Earth life, and that such a thing might translate to our position among alien life. A well known example is our endurance, which seems to be fairly well known among a lot of people today, but when I was young it was an extremely popular belief that humans only have our smarts going for us. You wouldn't believe how often I heard bullshit like the whole "humans couldn't survive in nature" as if we haven't evolved to do exactly that.

It's a real shame that it almost immediately got taken over by room temperature IQ people who took the whole thing to mean "genocide is a superpower". Even some of the better examples, like the whole Veil of Madness thing, sound crude and childish if I see them today. The entire subgenre was sadly stillborn, and the torch of its original intent is typically carried by communities that want to have nothing to do with what HFY became.
